"There are three books on your shelf that could teach you Newton. One is
a textbook and has proofs; one is a picture book and has apples; and
one is this chapter, which has neither and instead runs a small program
sixty times a second until the program's behavior BECOMES Newton's
second law.

Force equals mass times acceleration is not a slogan. It is an
algorithm. It says: given the forces on a thing, compute its
acceleration. Given the acceleration and a slice of time, compute the
change in velocity. Given the velocity and the same slice of time,
compute the change in position. Then start over. This is what
`(world/step)` does under the hood — thirty times a second by default,
sixty if we ask nicely. There is nothing mysterious about the loop.
The loop IS the physics.

We are going to build this loop three times. First for one body,
falling. Then for two bodies pulling on each other. Then for fifty
bodies pulling on ALL the other bodies, at which point structure will
emerge that nobody wrote down — no line of our code will say 'form a
cluster,' but a cluster will form anyway. That is emergence, and it is
the surprise this whole book is about.

---

## 1.1 One body under gravity

The smallest possible physics simulation is a dot that falls.

```scheme
;; A dot at (160, 40) falls under gravity, lands on a floor at 240.
(define (drop-one-dot)
  (world/reset!)
  (world/gravity! 0 0.5)          ;; a = (0, 0.5) px/frame^2
  (world/floor! 240)              ;; hard floor at y=240
  (let ((dot (world/spawn 'dot 160 40)))
    (entity/bounce! dot 0.0)      ;; no bounce
    (let loop ((n 60))
      (world/step)
      (if (> n 0) (loop (- n 1)) (entity/pos dot)))))

(drop-one-dot)
;; => (160.0 . 240.0)
```

Twenty acceleration units per second squared, forty pixels of headroom,
sixty frames. The dot lands. `world/step` is where the physics
actually happens; the rest of the program describes the world it is
happening in. If you strip the print and squint, this program is one
line: `(let loop ((n 60)) (world/step) (loop (- n 1)))`. Everything
else is setup.

## 1.2 What world/step is doing to your dot

Let's replace `(world/step)` with our own version. We will not
integrate the whole world — just this one dot — so we can watch each
part of the algorithm move on the page.

```scheme
;; Hand-rolled Euler integrator for one falling body.
(define (euler-drop steps)
  (let ((g  0.5)                     ;; acceleration
        (dt 1.0))                    ;; one frame = 1 unit of time
    (let loop ((n  steps)
               (y  40)
               (vy 0))
      (if (<= n 0)
          (cons y vy)
          (let* ((ay g)                        ;; acceleration this frame
                 (vy* (+ vy (* ay dt)))        ;; new velocity
                 (y*  (+ y  (* vy* dt))))      ;; new position (semi-implicit)
            (loop (- n 1) y* vy*))))))

(euler-drop 60)
;; => (930.0 . 30.0)   -> if we had no floor, this is where we'd be
```

Read that inner `let*` twice. First we compute the acceleration; then
the velocity that comes out of applying that acceleration for one
frame; then the position that comes out of moving at THAT NEW velocity
for one frame. This is semi-implicit Euler. If we had written
`(+ y (* vy dt))` with the OLD velocity, we would have plain-vanilla
Euler, which is worse. Appendix A shows the two side by side, and it
matters more than you might think — plain Euler adds a tiny bit of
energy every frame; a plain-Euler pendulum swings wider and wider until
it goes over the top. Semi-implicit Euler doesn't do that.

The `world/step` inside Motoi Scheme uses semi-implicit Euler as its
default. You can swap it — the appendix covers the swap — but the
default is chosen because it's the least amount of code that doesn't
blow up on the second pendulum.

## 1.3 Two bodies pulling on each other

One body under gravity is Newton's LAW. Two bodies pulling on each
other is Newton's UNIVERSAL law — the surprise is that gravity between
the Earth and an apple, and gravity between the Earth and the Moon,
and gravity between two marbles on a table, are all the SAME
phenomenon with different masses. We do not have to teach the marbles
about the apple. We just apply the formula.

```scheme
;; Two bodies. Each pulls on the other with F = G m1 m2 / r^2.
(define (two-body-attract)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((a (world/spawn 'a  80 120))
        (b (world/spawn 'b 240 120)))
    (entity/mass! a 5000)
    (entity/mass! b 5000)
    (entity/set-vel! a 0 -1.2)         ;; a drifts up
    (entity/set-vel! b 0  1.2)         ;; b drifts down
    (world/attract! a b 1.0)           ;; mutual gravity, G-effective = 1
    (world/attract! b a 1.0)
    (let loop ((n 400))
      (world/step)
      (if (> n 0) (loop (- n 1))
          (list (entity/pos a) (entity/pos b))))))

(two-body-attract)
;; => ((~89 ~118) (~231 ~122))    <- they drifted, then curled back
```

`world/attract!` installs a persistent inverse-square force from source
to target. We install it twice, once each way, because gravity is
mutual. Give them opposing initial velocities and they will curl
around each other in an ellipse, come back near their starting
positions, and do it again. It is a repeating orbit — the two-body
problem has closed-form solutions, and our numerical sim reproduces
one.

Notice the shape of the loop. Whether we have one body or two, the
outer loop is the same: `(world/step)` then check if we're done. This
is what makes the whole book possible — every simulation, from a
falling dot to a fifty-body cluster, uses this same shape. The only
thing that changes is what's in the world when the loop starts.

## 1.4 Many bodies — the arrival of emergence

Now fifty bodies. Each one pulls on every other one. We didn't tell
them to form a cluster; we told them to obey `F = G m1 m2 / r^2`.
Watch what happens.

```scheme
;; Fifty bodies, mutual gravity, no floor. Let them find their shape.
(define (cluster n)
  (world/reset!)
  (let loop ((i 0) (bodies '()))
    (if (>= i n)
        (bodies-attract-all bodies)
        (let* ((x  (+ 100 (* 200 (random))))
               (y  (+  80 (* 160 (random))))
               (vx (- (* 0.5 (random)) 0.25))
               (vy (- (* 0.5 (random)) 0.25))
               (b  (world/spawn 'star x y)))
          (entity/mass!    b (+ 50 (* 200 (random))))
          (entity/set-vel! b vx vy)
          (loop (+ i 1) (cons b bodies))))))

(define (bodies-attract-all bs)
  ;; Every body attracts every other body. (n^2) force installs.
  (for-each
    (lambda (a)
      (for-each
        (lambda (b)
          (when (not (eq? a b))
            (world/attract! a b 1.0)))
        bs))
    bs))

(cluster 50)
(let loop ((n 600)) (world/step) (when (> n 0) (loop (- n 1))))
```

After a few hundred frames you see it: the outliers get flung, the
inner bodies fall together, and a knot forms in the middle. Nothing
you wrote said 'form a knot.' The knot emerges because inverse-square
attraction pulls hard at short range, and once two heavy stars pass
close they capture each other, and once they capture each other other
stars fall in. Structure appears. This is the first surprise of the
book, and it will be repeated many times: give the pieces a rule,
apply it many times, and watch shapes appear that no line of code
demanded.

`phys/nbody` gives you the same effect without the `for-each` boilerplate:

```scheme
;; The same thing with the built-in n-body verb.
(define (cluster-nice n)
  (world/reset!)
  (let ((bs (phys/nbody-spawn n
              :region   '(100 80 300 240)
              :mass     '(50 . 250)
              :vel      '(-0.25 . 0.25)
              :G        1.0)))
    bs))

(cluster-nice 50)
```

`phys/nbody-spawn` installs the (n(n-1)) attractions for you and
returns the list of entities. Under the hood: exactly the code above.

---

## 1.5 The four routing patterns in a simulation loop

The book on the shelf next to this one — Book of Systems — teaches
four patterns the runtime uses everywhere: composition, orchestration,
in-routing, and routing. Even a one-chapter simulation touches all
four. This section names them so you notice, next time, where the
pattern is.

**Composition.** `world/step` is not one verb; it is many small verbs
composed. Under the hood it does: apply forces, integrate velocities,
integrate positions, resolve constraints, check collisions, notify
handlers. We compose it into our own step for the hand-rolled dropper.
The `bodies-attract-all` function above is composition of `for-each`
with `world/attract!`.

**Orchestration.** The `let loop ((n 600))` is an orchestration of
`world/step` across time. It waits, it counts down, it eventually
returns. A more elaborate orchestration would `world/step` for 300
frames, `world/snapshot` the state, `world/step` for another 300
frames, and diff the snapshots to detect equilibrium.

**In-routing.** When two stars collide, the physics engine has to route
the collision event to the right handler. We haven't wired one yet, but
in chapter 4 you'll see:

```scheme
(world/on-collision! 'star 'star
  (lambda (a b) (entity/despawn! b)))  ;; merge two stars, keep one
```

The `'star 'star` is an in-route: 'when an entity tagged star hits
another entity tagged star, dispatch here.'

**Routing.** The result of the simulation has to go somewhere. Right
now our functions return positions to the REPL. In a running world,
each frame the positions route to the framebuffer via
`(paint-circle x y r color)`, the collision events route to an audio
handler, and any interesting emergent-cluster-forming events could
route to Cortex as 'this initial condition led to a bound cluster.'

Four patterns, all in one 60-line simulation. You'll see them again
in every chapter.

---

## 1.6 Common desktop tasks

An operator running a physical-goods shop asked the runtime once: 'if I hang
a light fixture from a chain, and someone opens the front door and a
wind comes through, how long until the fixture stops swinging?' That
is a one-body simulation. It is `world/gravity!` + `entity/pin!` + an
initial `world/impulse!` + `entity/friction!`, and it runs in eighty
lines. Chapter 3 builds it. The point today: one-body simulation is not
just for kids in astronomy class — it is a tool for answering everyday
questions about the physical world.

Another operator asked: 'if two of my parking spots are close together
and both are magnetized to pull cars in, will cars end up in one spot
or split evenly?' That is a two-body-attractor problem, and the answer
depends on the ratio of attraction strength to car separation. You can
find out with `two-body-attract` above; change 5000 to 2500 in one
mass and re-run. This is the shop-side use of simulation.

## 1.7 Try this yourself

1. Change gravity to (0.5, 0) — sideways gravity. Re-run
   `drop-one-dot`. Where does it land?
2. In `euler-drop`, change the order of the two updates so `y` is
   computed with `vy` instead of `vy*` (plain Euler). Run for 200
   steps. Compare the y-value against the exact formula
   `y = y0 + 0.5 * g * t^2`. Which is closer to the truth?
3. In `two-body-attract`, make body b's mass 10× body a's mass. Do
   both bodies still swing, or does the small one orbit the big one?
4. In `cluster`, start with 200 bodies instead of 50. Does the cluster
   form faster or slower? Why?

## 1.8 Pitfalls

**Blow-up.** If you set gravity too high and the timestep too big, the
dot skips through the floor. Semi-implicit Euler helps but doesn't
cure. Fix: smaller timestep, or use `world/floor!` which enforces
after every substep, or clamp velocity via `entity/max-speed!`.

**Ghost forces.** If you `world/attract!` in a running loop instead of
once, you install a fresh attractor every frame. Bodies fly away at
absurd speed. Install force relationships ONCE outside the loop.

**Symmetric-vs-antisymmetric.** `world/attract! a b` is 'a attracts
toward b.' Not 'they attract each other.' If you want mutual, call it
twice. This is a source of many first-week simulation bugs.

---

Next chapter: two bodies linked by a spring, then ten of them in a
chain, then a 15×15 grid of them in a piece of cloth. Same
`world/step`, same integrator, one new primitive: `world/link!`.")
